      <div class="span5 copy">
        <p>
          Recently we have all been made aware of the ability and willingness of the government
          to collect and store the personal communications of every citizen.  The major phone
          companies have also displayed their willingness to let the government listen in and
          read everything we say.  This project will propose an open protocol for peer-to-peer
          encryption of text data.  This is intended to work over existing text infrastuctures
          such as text messaging, e-mail, Twitter, Facebook, etc.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row-fluid section2">
      <div class="span5 offset1 copy copy-right">
        <p>
          By using existing communication channels, this product will not introduce a dependency
          upon our servers.  Once you have an application using our encryption system installed,
          your messages can be sent over open systems without their content being read by any
          observers.  Only those with whom you have securely shared a key will be able to
          decipher your messages.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="span5 asset">
        <img class="img-polaroid" alt="Barack Obama using a magnifying glass again." src="http://i.imgur.com/JCBCY6T.jpg">
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row-fluid section2">
      <div class="span10 offset1">
        <p>
          The recent closings of Lavabit and Silent Circle e-mail services display both the
          increasing aggressiveness of the government and the futility of entrusting encryption
          keys to even the best-intentioned companies.  A system is needed in which only the
          parties at the endpoints are able to successfully encode and decode the secret data.
          This project was originally intended to release an application implementing such a
          system. But such an application would likely be taken down through government action.
          The project focus as therefore changed to defining open protocols for the various
          media platforms to which any programmer can code compatible application layers.  An
          application release my follow at a later time.
        </p>
